reviews.mitigation:
Make the TypeScript declarations accurately reflect runtime behavior and avoid contradictory generic constraints. Suggested fixes:
- Remove the unused generic parameter from the primitive overloads or avoid an unnecessary generic on all overloads. E.g.:
  declare function ToObject(value: number): Number;
  declare function ToObject(value: boolean): Boolean;
  declare function ToObject(value: string): String;
  declare function ToObject(value: bigint): BigInt;
  declare function ToObject<T extends object>(value: T): T;
  export = ToObject;
- Alternatively, collapse into clearer signatures that exclude null/undefined at the type level so callers see the possibility of a thrown TypeError, e.g. use NonNullable types where appropriate or document/annotate that null|undefined are not accepted.
- Ensure the package README/type comments explicitly state the function throws on null/undefined and that boxed primitives are returned for primitive inputs so callers handle them safely.
- Consider using stricter types (or adding comments) to discourage merging untrusted objects into prototypes and to remind consumers to validate external inputs before using Object APIs.

