reviews.mitigation:
Avoid using direct object spread/assign onto a normal Object prototype when merging untrusted objects. Possible mitigations include:
- Create a null-prototype target and copy only safe own properties: Object.assign(Object.create(null), first, second) and then, if needed, recreate a plain object while explicitly copying filtered keys. A null-prototype object does not inherit the __proto__ setter so properties named "__proto__" will remain as ordinary keys rather than mutate the prototype.
- Filter out dangerous property names before copying (e.g., "__proto__", "prototype", "constructor").
- Copy properties using Object.keys()/Object.getOwnPropertyNames() and Object.defineProperty onto a null-prototype target to avoid invoking accessor setters on Object.prototype.
- Use a small helper to perform a safe merge that explicitly ignores or rejects prototype-polluting keys.
Example safe pattern:
  const safeMerge = (a: any, b: any) => {
    const out = Object.create(null);
    for (const key of Object.keys(a || {})) {
      if (key === '__proto__' || key === 'constructor' || key === 'prototype') continue;
      out[key] = (a as any)[key];
    }
    for (const key of Object.keys(b || {})) {
      if (key === '__proto__' || key === 'constructor' || key === 'prototype') continue;
      out[key] = (b as any)[key];
    }
    return out as any;
  };
Apply such a pattern in mergeShapes or validate/normalize inputs upstream before calling mergeShapes.

