This localization module constructs message strings by directly interpolating values from the validation runtime (e.g. _issue.prefix, _issue.suffix, _issue.includes, _issue.pattern, issue.values, issue.keys) without any escaping. RELEVANT_CONTEXT states these message-producing functions are called with values derived from application input and schema, which are attacker-controllable. If an application inserts these returned strings into an HTML page or other interpreter context without encoding, an attacker can craft validation inputs or schema-derived values that contain HTML or script payloads, leading to DOM‑based XSS or other injection attacks. For example, returning `Eilutė privalo prasidėti "${_issue.prefix}"` will place raw _issue.prefix into the output; if that output is inserted into innerHTML, it becomes executable.

Additionally, parsedTypeFromType uses data.constructor.name in forming type names (see snippet below), which can also include attacker-influenced strings when validating objects with crafted constructors, increasing the same risk:

if (Object.getPrototypeOf(data) !== Object.prototype && data.constructor) {
  return data.constructor.name;
}

All of these locations directly reflect untrusted values into messages that are likely displayed to end users.

